      "text": "\"The Pretence of Knowledge\" is the title of a [http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economic-sciences/laureates/1974/hayek-lecture.html lecture (web page)] given by Friedrich Hayek on receiving the \"Nobel Prize\" (for Economics) in 1974."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e6b48f6030cd3359",
      "text": "In it Hayek bemoans the rise of the \"scientistic attitude\" within the field of economics and more broadly in other social science disciplines. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3d6ea9813c4889d9",
      "text": "The problem with this attitude is that the social sciences deal with phenomena of organised complexity. Phenomena that require full information about the individual components of a structure in order for predictions to be made."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2d48ec6606845c53",
      "text": "The use of mathematics enables the use of statistics information in place of full information about each of the components. But this creates an illusion that this can be used for determination and prediction. Appears related to \"[[confusion of simulation with prediction]]\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0aaafac2fccd3116",
      "text": "There is a pretence of knowledge. That contributes to an increasingly belief in our power to predict and control that can be \"applies to the processes of society\" and \"enable us to mould society entirely to our liking\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf537641674df21e",
      "text": "It is argued that this is a capability that the public expects, due to the successes of science. This public perception means that there will be those that will pretend (and perhaps believe) that they can meet this perception."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dc179e9791c3816b",
      "text": "There are \"absolute obstacles to the prediction of specific events\" in these fields and acting as if we can \"may itself become a serious obstacle to the advance of the human intellect\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5bc58d4768fd13f6",
      "text": "Rather than assume that you can acquire the full knowledge required to \"shape the results as the craftsman shapes his handiwork\", the suggested approach is to rather \"cultivate a growth by providing the appropriate environment, in the manner in which the gardner does this for his plants\"."
    },
